04204nam a22005655i 9780773587670DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20122012xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735876707 a10.1515/97807735876702doi  a(DE-B1597)656522  a(OCoLC)818016737  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aPG3948.V88bZ87 2012eb 7aBIO0070002bisacsh04a891.7/9332231 aSoroka, Mykola, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFaces of Displacement :bThe Writings of Volodymyr Vynnychenko /cMykola Soroka. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (248 p.) :b12 b&w photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface -- tA Vynnychenko Chronology -- tIntroduction: Displacement and Identity -- tFirst Displacement, 1907–1914 -- tÉmigré -- tExpatriate/Traveler -- tExile -- tSecond Displacement, 1920–1951 -- tUtopist, 1920–1925 -- tUniversalist, 1925–1941 -- tHomecoming, 1941–1951 -- tConclusions -- tChronological List of Vynnychenko’s Works -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  a"Whom do our people read? Vynnychenko. Whom do people talk about if it concerns literature? Vynnychenko. Whom do they buy? Again, Vynnychenko." So wrote Mykhailo Kotsiubynsky about the young Volodymyr Vynnychenko. An innovative and provocative writer, Vynnychenko was also a charismatic revolutionary and politician who responded to the dramatic upheavals of the first half of the twentieth century by challenging old values and bringing forward new ideas about human relationships. Despite his inseparable association with Ukraine, what is often overlooked is the fact that Vynnychenko wrote the majority of his works outside his native land following his flight from Tsarist and Soviet tyranny. In this ground-breaking study, Mykola Soroka draws on contemporary theories of displacement to show how Vynnychenko's expatriate status determined his worldview, his choice of literary devices, and his attitudes toward his homeland and hostlands. Soroka considers concepts of identity to study the intertwined experiences of the writer - as an exile, émigré, expatriate, traveler, and nomad - and to demonstrate how these experiences invigorated his art and left a lasting impact on his work. The first book-length study in English on Volodymyr Vynnychenko, Faces of Displacement is an insightful examination of an exiled writer that sheds new light on the challenges faced by the displaced.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEmigration and immigration in literature. 0aExile (Punishment) in literature. 0aIdentity (Philosophical concept) in literature. 0aPolitics in literature. 0aTravel in literature. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Literary.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2012z978311127413308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2012z978311127716540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077358767040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773587670423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773587670/original  a978-3-11-127413-3  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2012b2012  a978-3-11-127716-5  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2012b2012  aGBV-deGruyter-alles